  "duration": 141.74030937600003,
  "text": " As I've also done recently, today we're going to lean on the Viable System model by Stafford Beard. We shan't see the model again, so let's take a quick rehearsal of it. Now, by the way, if you want to read more about this model, you've got the original text, or my go-to book is this one here, The Fractal Organization by Patrick Hoversout. Easy to read, explains the concepts, brilliant. Viable system, a system that's able to maintain a separate existence. An existence in what? The environment. So what we're going to do is we're going to draw it up like this. There's my big E for the environment. So every system, this goes from a human body to the whole organisation, has its primary activities that it's doing, and we represent those by, we'll call those operations O. And then we also have a management function, which has various functions that it's going to do. So we're going to call that M. So what we've got is the environment, operations and management. First we have system one. System one is made up of the primary activities that we do. Now when we're doing structure work, we make certain choices on how we gonna divide up system one that for another time But for now what we have is these functions here which are system one so we got the primary activities these activities are now required to be coordinated so they don bang into each other when they doing their stuff which is system two coordination system two make sure these don't bang into each other now what we have is system three which is about the management of how all these shows fit together allocating resources and the like and if the environment never changed that's all we'd ever need however in the real world we're also going to have a changing environment, which is why in order to be viable, we need to have development, which is system four, and development occurs through knowledge and interaction with the environment, as you can see there. Finally, all of this exists for some sort of purpose, which is system five, which I like to draw as a little house at the top there. So five systems, if we have all five systems working, we have ourselves a viable organization. And to get this working, we need information flows between all the systems to make sure that things work. Now, the VSM has uses in two ways, one of which is diagnosing where issues might be, and the second one is actually designing your organization using these principles so it's going to work. This applies to a whole organization. Then the same five systems are necessary to have in any given department, any given team, even inside a human body. All these five systems are present. That's all for now. See you next time.",
